contract "BUG-2026-008" {
  title = "Sprint progress ignores batch membership and contracts field"
  status = "complete"
  slug = "sprint-batch-progress"
  goal = "computeSprintStatus uses QueryArtifacts(References: sprintID) which only matches contracts with a direct sprint field. Three gaps: (1) batch is missing from the link fields in matchArtifact, so contracts grouped via batch are invisible to reference queries. (2) No transitive resolution: contract.batch -> batch.sprint is not walked, so batch membership never propagates to sprint context. (3) The sprint's own contracts field (comma-separated list) is completely ignored by computeSprintStatus. Result: sprint progress shows 0/0 unless every contract has sprint=SPR-X set individually."
  justifies = "CON-2026-125"
  created_at = 2026-03-04T09:19:59Z
  updated_at = 2026-03-04T10:35:10Z

  section "Root Cause" {
    text = """
FieldDef has no link/reference semantic. Fields are modeled as data (string, enum, bool) but never as edges in the artifact graph. The graph structure is implicit — baked into hardcoded string arrays in query.go and chain.go. When a new relationship like batch is introduced via config.mos, the graph-aware code cannot discover it automatically.

Two hardcoded lists exist and are already inconsistent:
- query.go:164 — [justifies, implements, documents, sprint, parent, depends_on]
- chain.go:62 — [justifies, implements, documents]

Neither includes batch. Every new link field silently breaks graph queries.

Additionally, computeSprintStatus has no transitive resolution. It can only find contracts that directly set sprint=SPR-X. It cannot follow contract.batch -> batch membership to resolve sprint scope.

Fix requires CON-2026-125: declarative link fields in FieldDef so the registry drives graph traversal."""
  }

  coverage {

    unit {
      applies = true
    }

    integration {
      applies = true
    }
  }
}

